00:46:08,936 --> 00:46:10,979
Please read this.
Thank you.

770
00:46:11,104 --> 00:46:14,066
Would you like to take one of
these, please, to fill out?

771
00:46:14,233 --> 00:46:16,443
Three square meals a day.

772
00:46:16,610 --> 00:46:17,653
Three square meals a day.

773
00:46:17,819 --> 00:46:20,405
Young man, enlist
and serve your country.

774
00:46:20,531 --> 00:46:22,699
Three square meals a day,
gentlemen.

775
00:46:22,824 --> 00:46:23,742
If you're interested,

776
00:46:23,867 --> 00:46:25,410
I suggest you read this
and consider joining up.

777
00:46:25,536 --> 00:46:27,079
AMSTERDAM:
Everywhere you went,

778
00:46:27,162 --> 00:46:28,747
people talked about
the draft.

779
00:46:28,872 --> 00:46:31,917
Now, you could buy
your way out for $300,

780
00:46:32,042 --> 00:46:34,002
but who had $300?

781
00:46:34,127 --> 00:46:36,922
For us, it might as well
have been $3 millions.

782
00:46:37,005 --> 00:46:38,423
The recruiters...

783
00:46:38,507 --> 00:46:41,552
they was too scared of
the gangs to come after us.

784
00:46:41,677 --> 00:46:46,348
Besides, we never dreamt the war
would ever touch New York.

785
00:46:46,473 --> 00:46:48,141
JENNY: Good morning, sir.

786
00:46:49,852 --> 00:46:51,645
You!

787
00:46:51,770 --> 00:46:53,689
Don't you run into me.

788
00:46:54,982 --> 00:46:56,817
Fair enough.

789
00:47:00,988 --> 00:47:01,905
Oh! Oh!

790
00:47:01,989 --> 00:47:03,699
I said, "Don't run into me."

791
00:47:03,824 --> 00:47:05,158
Well, sorry.

792
00:47:11,373 --> 00:47:12,791
Everything in place?

793
00:47:12,875 --> 00:47:15,252
It seems so.

794
00:47:15,377 --> 00:47:18,130
Well, then, I leave you in the
grace and favor of the Lord.

795
00:47:18,213 --> 00:47:19,548
- That's right.
- Thank you.

796
00:47:28,056 --> 00:47:29,975
Oh, the dirty mab!

797
00:47:35,189 --> 00:47:36,648
- Oh, no.
- Ah.

798
00:47:36,732 --> 00:47:38,734
- I'm sorry.
- Ah, allow me.

799
00:47:39,818 --> 00:47:40,986
[Coin clatters]

800
00:47:41,069 --> 00:47:42,988
Thank you kindly, sir.

801
00:47:43,071 --> 00:47:45,240
Oh, it's my pleasure.

802
00:47:45,365 --> 00:47:48,202
I hope you won't think me
rude if I speak.

803
00:47:48,285 --> 00:47:50,704
I wouldn't want to
appear forward.

804
00:47:50,787 --> 00:47:54,291
Well, sir, that depends
on what you say.

805
00:47:54,416 --> 00:47:56,126
[Both chuckling]

806
00:47:56,251 --> 00:47:58,712
Ahh...

807
00:48:03,300 --> 00:48:04,593
Would you call me reckless

808
00:48:04,718 --> 00:48:07,763
if I said you were the
prettiest girl in New York?

809
00:48:07,888 --> 00:48:09,306
Only New York?

810
00:48:09,389 --> 00:48:11,892
[Both chuckling]

811
00:48:11,975 --> 00:48:13,894
This is my stop.

812
00:48:13,977 --> 00:48:15,187
MAN: Ho!

813
00:48:15,270 --> 00:48:18,899
Ah! May I walk with you
a little, then?

814
00:48:19,024 --> 00:48:21,902
That, sir, would be too bold.

815
00:48:22,027 --> 00:48:24,530
[Hoofbeats approach]

816
00:48:26,323 --> 00:48:28,825
Ho!

817
00:48:48,887 --> 00:48:52,474
AMSTERDAM: For every lay,
we had a different name.

818
00:48:52,599 --> 00:48:55,018
An angler put a hook
on the end of a stick

819
00:48:55,102 --> 00:48:58,063
to drop behind store windows
and doors.

820
00:48:58,146 --> 00:49:01,191
An autumn diver picked
your pocket in church.

821
00:49:01,316 --> 00:49:04,862
A badger gets a fellow
into bed with a girl,

822
00:49:04,987 --> 00:49:07,948
then robs his pockets
while they're on the go.

823
00:49:08,073 --> 00:49:11,952
Jenny was a bludget...
a girl pickpocket...

824
00:49:12,035 --> 00:49:15,581
and... a turtledove.

825
00:49:18,000 --> 00:49:21,044
A turtledove goes uptown
dressed like a housemaid,

826
00:49:21,128 --> 00:49:22,546
picks out a fine house,

827
00:49:22,671 --> 00:49:25,132
and goes right through
the back door...

828
00:49:25,215 --> 00:49:26,800
robs you blind.

829
00:49:28,594 --> 00:49:32,097
It takes a lot of sand
to be a turtledove.

830
00:49:32,181 --> 00:49:33,640
[Silverware clattering]

831
00:49:39,730 --> 00:49:41,648
[Indistinct conversation]

832
00:49:54,036 --> 00:49:55,704
I'll have my medal back.

833
00:49:55,829 --> 00:49:57,789
Oh, Jesus!

834
00:49:57,915 --> 00:49:58,832
Unh!

835
00:49:58,916 --> 00:50:01,335
[Both panting]

836
00:50:01,460 --> 00:50:04,171
[Breathing deeply]

837
00:50:04,296 --> 00:50:05,672
Don't do that again.

838
00:50:05,797 --> 00:50:09,218
Aah! Listen, I said
don't do that...

839
00:50:10,385 --> 00:50:12,596
Go back to the Points
and leave me to my business,

840
00:50:12,679 --> 00:50:15,682
or I will open your throat,
so help me God.

841
00:50:19,061 --> 00:50:20,354
All right.

842
00:50:22,189 --> 00:50:23,524
Go on, then.

843
00:50:26,360 --> 00:50:27,569
I would.

844
00:50:29,988 --> 00:50:31,615
Go on, then.

845
00:50:36,119 --> 00:50:39,039
[Breathing heavily]

846
00:50:49,925 --> 00:50:50,884
[Gasps]

847
00:50:53,887 --> 00:50:56,640
Now... give me back my medal.

848
00:50:56,723 --> 00:50:58,392
Make it quick!

849
00:51:06,316 --> 00:51:08,527
I don't know
which one's yours.

850
00:51:15,742 --> 00:51:18,245
Suppose I help myself
to everything?

851
00:51:19,246 --> 00:51:20,956
Huh?

852
00:51:21,081 --> 00:51:22,916
Suppose you do.

853
00:51:27,963 --> 00:51:30,007
[Medals jingling]

854
00:51:30,132 --> 00:51:31,341
[Gasps]

855
00:52:01,413 --> 00:52:03,290
May I walk with you
a little, then?

856
00:52:03,415 --> 00:52:04,750
[Chuckles softly]

857
00:52:10,214 --> 00:52:12,424
[Hoofbeats approach]

858
00:52:12,508 --> 00:52:16,011
What do you suppose a fellow
could earn up here in a day?

859
00:52:16,136 --> 00:52:17,596
Maybe we could pal in
together.

860
00:52:17,721 --> 00:52:21,225
Oh, I think you're a bit rough
for this sort of game.

861
00:52:21,350 --> 00:52:23,727
Besides, I work alone.

862
00:52:23,810 --> 00:52:24,811
Alone?

863
00:52:24,937 --> 00:52:27,314
Well, what do you quarter
to the Butcher?

864
00:52:27,439 --> 00:52:28,941
Me... nothing.

865
00:52:29,066 --> 00:52:30,108
Nothing?!

866
00:52:30,234 --> 00:52:32,653
The Butcher and me
have a special arrangement.

867
00:52:39,076 --> 00:52:40,994
I don't want to see you again.

868
00:52:41,078 --> 00:52:42,204
Well, I don't blame you.

869
00:52:44,706 --> 00:52:47,376
JACK: Pennies in their pockets
and hope in their eyes,

870
00:52:47,501 --> 00:52:49,711
they peer to the west,

871
00:52:49,837 --> 00:52:54,424
searching the horizon for a
glimpse of land and salvation...

872
00:52:54,550 --> 00:52:57,636
Ah... a glimpse of America.

873
00:52:57,803 --> 00:52:59,179
GREELEY:
Seeing all this poverty

874
00:52:59,304 --> 00:53:00,973
must be most unsettling,
Miss Schermerhorn.

875
00:53:01,056 --> 00:53:02,307
AMSTERDAM:
Some days, of course,

876
00:53:02,391 --> 00:53:05,060
the uptown gangs
come down to us.

877
00:53:05,185 --> 00:53:07,813
The Schermerhorns was one
of the oldest families

878
00:53:07,896 --> 00:53:09,064
in New York.

879
00:53:09,189 --> 00:53:10,691
They didn't run the city,

880
00:53:10,816 --> 00:53:13,735
but they was listened to quite
carefully by them that did.

881
00:53:13,861 --> 00:53:15,612
Commissioner Brunt said
you wished to view the Points

882
00:53:15,696 --> 00:53:18,198
in all its splendor
and squalor.

883
00:53:18,323 --> 00:53:20,534
"Spare nothing concerning
the conditions," said he.

884
00:53:20,659 --> 00:53:23,620
Yeah, nothing except
our safety, Constable.

885
00:53:23,704 --> 00:53:25,372
I'm sure we can be
in no danger

886
00:53:25,497 --> 00:53:27,499
while we're in the constable's
company, my dear.

887
00:53:27,666 --> 00:53:30,127
Quite so, madam. Witness.

888
00:53:37,718 --> 00:53:39,678
Shall we continue on?

889
00:53:39,803 --> 00:53:41,555
What, you dare
to leave it there?

890
00:53:41,638 --> 00:53:46,226
Safe as a bank, Mr. Greeley,
since all know it's mine.

891
00:53:46,351 --> 00:53:48,103
Is that man drunk?

892
00:53:48,228 --> 00:53:50,814
Oh, dead as Good Friday, miss.

893
00:53:55,235 --> 00:53:57,029
Good day to you, Mulraney.

894
00:53:57,112 --> 00:53:58,697
- JACK: Boys.
- Jack.

895
00:53:58,822 --> 00:53:59,865
Slum sociable?

896
00:53:59,990 --> 00:54:01,867
Fact-finding, reforms-studying.

897
00:54:01,950 --> 00:54:03,368
May I present Mr. And...

898
00:54:03,452 --> 00:54:05,412
The Schermerhorns
of 5th Avenue

899
00:54:05,537 --> 00:54:08,415
scarcely require
an introduction from you, Jack.

900
00:54:08,498 --> 00:54:09,958
Schermerhorn, indeed,
and their daughter.

901
00:54:10,083 --> 00:54:11,335
This gentleman,
of course, is...

902
00:54:11,418 --> 00:54:12,920
Mr. Horace Greeley,
the famous publisher.

903
00:54:13,045 --> 00:54:14,755
A pleasure and an honor,
sir.

904
00:54:14,838 --> 00:54:16,256
...of the "Tribune."

905
00:54:16,340 --> 00:54:17,925
I'm William Cutting.

906
00:54:19,051 --> 00:54:20,761
How do you do, Mr. Cutting?

907
00:54:22,763 --> 00:54:24,723
As of this moment,
extremely well, thank you.

908
00:54:24,848 --> 00:54:26,767
How do you do?

909
00:54:26,850 --> 00:54:29,394
Mmm, orange blossom...
delicious.

910
00:54:29,478 --> 00:54:31,522
Mr. Cutting is, uh...

911
00:54:31,605 --> 00:54:34,107
What a peach. She could have
a fine career on the stage.

912
00:54:34,233 --> 00:54:35,776
...one of Five Points'
local...

913
00:54:35,943 --> 00:54:37,152
Pleasure to meet you, sir.

914
00:54:37,319 --> 00:54:38,695
...leaders.
- Mr. Greeley...

915
00:54:38,779 --> 00:54:39,905
Pleased to meet you,
Mr. Cutting.

916
00:54:40,072 --> 00:54:41,406
Five Points welcomes you.

917
00:54:41,490 --> 00:54:44,326
You are welcome to these streets
and will pass in safety.

918
00:54:44,451 --> 00:54:47,412
Oh, I'll see to their safety.

919
00:54:47,496 --> 00:54:48,956
Thank you, Bill.

920
00:54:49,081 --> 00:54:50,290
Here we are.

921
00:54:50,374 --> 00:54:51,458
Good day, lads.

922
00:54:51,583 --> 00:54:53,460
Criminal's braggadocio,
you see.

923
00:54:53,544 --> 00:54:55,587
- He knows who I am.
- Oh, indeed, sir.

924
00:54:55,712 --> 00:54:58,257
You're well-known
in these parts.

925
00:54:58,340 --> 00:55:01,760
I must say that I find that
strangely flattering.

926
00:55:01,844 --> 00:55:03,637
I never did like crushers.

927
00:55:03,720 --> 00:55:05,889
Well, draw it mild, son...
Happy Jack don't fill his lungs

928
00:55:05,973 --> 00:55:07,766
without I tell him
he may do so.

929
00:55:07,891 --> 00:55:11,854
<i># He'll spend at</i>
<i>The Odd Fellows' club #</i>

930
00:55:11,979 --> 00:55:14,815
<i># At the office or store,</i>
<i>He was kept #</i>

931
00:55:14,940 --> 00:55:19,319
<i># He'll pretend,</i>
<i>And so he was, too #</i>

932
00:55:19,403 --> 00:55:21,154
<i># Drinking rum with a friend #</i>

933
00:55:21,280 --> 00:55:23,949
You think my watch would be safe
up on that lamppost, Bill?

934
00:55:24,032 --> 00:55:26,702
<i># At the office or store,</i>
<i>He was kept #</i>

935
00:55:26,827 --> 00:55:29,663
Why don't you hang it
up there and see?

936
00:55:29,746 --> 00:55:31,665
<i># He'll pretend,</i>
<i>And so he was, too #</i>

937
00:55:31,790 --> 00:55:35,002
- Someday.
<i>- # Drinking rum with a friend #</i>

938
00:55:35,127 --> 00:55:37,004
Someday is right.

939
00:55:37,129 --> 00:55:38,630
<i># Fortune's a false</i>
<i>And a fickle young jade #</i>

940
00:55:38,755 --> 00:55:39,840
This a new lad?

941
00:55:39,965 --> 00:55:42,926
Just another
bastard son of Erin

942
00:55:43,010 --> 00:55:46,471
I folded in the warmth
of my embrace.

943
00:55:46,638 --> 00:55:49,516
<i># And the best</i>
<i>Of all blessings #</i>

944
00:55:49,641 --> 00:55:50,225
Hey!

945
00:55:50,350 --> 00:55:51,852
Just want to see
your face, son.

946
00:55:51,977 --> 00:55:55,063
<i>- # Is a kind, loving husband #</i>
- No harm intended.

947
00:55:55,189 --> 00:55:58,275
<i># And a good-tempered wife #</i>

948
00:55:58,358 --> 00:56:00,485
<i># And the best</i>
<i>Of all blessings #</i>

949
00:56:00,569 --> 00:56:03,947
<i># We can meet in this life #</i>

950
00:56:04,031 --> 00:56:06,992
<i># Is a kind, loving husband #</i>

951
00:56:07,075 --> 00:56:10,996
<i># And a good-tempered wife #</i>

952
00:56:11,079 --> 00:56:12,873
[Irish music plays]

953
00:56:17,503 --> 00:56:21,632
You get to know a lot
butchering meat.

954
00:56:21,715 --> 00:56:23,634
We're made up
of the same things...

955
00:56:23,717 --> 00:56:26,887
flesh and blood,
tissue, organs.

956
00:56:28,096 --> 00:56:30,682
I love to work with pigs.

957
00:56:30,807 --> 00:56:33,852
The nearest thing in nature
to the flesh of a man

958
00:56:33,936 --> 00:56:35,521
is the flesh of a pig.

959
00:56:35,646 --> 00:56:37,439
Pig, huh?

960
00:56:37,564 --> 00:56:38,815
That's right.

961
00:56:38,899 --> 00:56:40,734
This is for you, Mother.

962
00:56:44,071 --> 00:56:45,405
Here you go.

963
00:56:45,489 --> 00:56:47,658
- God bless you, Mr. Cutting.
- God bless you.

964
00:56:48,742 --> 00:56:49,910
She ain't really my mother.

965
00:56:50,077 --> 00:56:52,079
[Chuckles]
I knew that, Bill.

966
00:56:57,167 --> 00:56:59,878
This is the liver...

967
00:56:59,962 --> 00:57:01,922
the kidneys...

968
00:57:02,005 --> 00:57:03,674
the heart.

969
00:57:03,757 --> 00:57:05,092
This is a wound.

970
00:57:05,217 --> 00:57:07,469
The stomach
will bleed and bleed.

971
00:57:07,594 --> 00:57:09,304
This is a kill.

972
00:57:09,429 --> 00:57:11,014
This is a kill.

973
00:57:11,098 --> 00:57:13,016
Main artery...

974
00:57:13,100 --> 00:57:15,602
this is a kill.

975
00:57:15,686 --> 00:57:17,729
You try.

976
00:57:21,441 --> 00:57:23,068
Go ahead.

977
00:57:47,968 --> 00:57:49,052
The lung. Good.

978
00:57:49,136 --> 00:57:50,762
Don't foul the blade
on the rib.

979
00:57:50,888 --> 00:57:53,515
Very good... main artery.

980
00:57:53,640 --> 00:57:54,725
Bleed him slow.

981
00:57:54,850 --> 00:57:57,686
Let him think about it
for a while... slow death.

982
00:57:57,811 --> 00:57:59,771
Good.

983
00:58:00,898 --> 00:58:03,150
TWEED: You will each bill
the city $5,000 a month

984
00:58:03,233 --> 00:58:05,652
for supplies and services,
of which you'll receive 10%.

985
00:58:05,777 --> 00:58:07,446
Bill!

986
00:58:07,529 --> 00:58:09,990
Mr. Killoran will work out the
details. Thank you, gentlemen!

987
00:58:10,073 --> 00:58:12,701
That's how we do things
around Tammany, gentlemen.

988
00:58:12,826 --> 00:58:14,161
Who's this, then?

989
00:58:14,286 --> 00:58:16,538
[Birds chirping]

990
00:58:16,663 --> 00:58:18,540
BILL: Thank you, boys.

991
00:58:18,665 --> 00:58:19,958
Good day, sir.

992
00:58:32,137 --> 00:58:34,348
You got something
on your mind?

993
00:58:37,559 --> 00:58:39,895
Bill's taken
quite a liking to you.

994
00:58:42,022 --> 00:58:44,525
Now, if you're
up to something...

995
00:58:44,650 --> 00:58:46,360
<i>bene.</i>

996
00:58:46,485 --> 00:58:48,779
Only I don't want
no part in it.

997
00:58:53,200 --> 00:58:55,953
I was in Hellgate
for 16 years.

998
00:58:56,036 --> 00:58:57,162
[Chuckles]

999
00:58:57,287 --> 00:58:59,456
I'm just trying
to make my way, is all...

1000
00:58:59,540 --> 00:59:00,624
just like you.

1001
00:59:03,043 --> 00:59:05,337
Unless, of course,
you got a better notion.

1002
00:59:06,547 --> 00:59:07,881
No.

1003
00:59:08,006 --> 00:59:11,552
Bill, I can't get
a day's work done

1004
00:59:11,677 --> 00:59:13,428
for all the good citizens
coming in here

1005
00:59:13,554 --> 00:59:15,889
to harass me
about crime in the Points.

1006
00:59:16,014 --> 00:59:20,227
Some even go so far as to
accuse Tammany of connivance

1007
00:59:20,352 --> 00:59:22,980
in this so-called
rampant criminality.

1008
00:59:23,063 --> 00:59:24,398
What am I to do?

1009
00:59:24,481 --> 00:59:26,525
I can't have this.
Something has to be done.

1010
00:59:26,608 --> 00:59:27,860
What do you have in mind?

1011
00:59:27,943 --> 00:59:29,444
I don't know.

1012
00:59:29,570 --> 00:59:31,446
I think maybe
we should hang someone.

1013
00:59:31,572 --> 00:59:33,115
Who?

1014
00:59:33,240 --> 00:59:36,285
No one important, necessarily.
Average men will do...

1015
00:59:36,410 --> 00:59:39,371
back-alley amusers
with no affiliations.

1016
00:59:39,454 --> 00:59:40,747
How many?

1017
00:59:40,831 --> 00:59:42,082
Three or four.

1018
00:59:42,207 --> 00:59:43,500
[Birds chirping]

1019
00:59:43,584 --> 00:59:44,501
Which?

1020
00:59:44,585 --> 00:59:46,253
Four.

1021
00:59:47,421 --> 00:59:51,633
You stand here convicted
varyingly

1022
00:59:51,758 --> 00:59:56,722
of lewdness, jackrolling,
sneak-thievery,

1023
00:59:56,847 --> 01:00:01,685
chloral-hydrating, sodomy,
strangulation,

1024
01:00:01,768 --> 01:00:05,772
and enthusiastic corruption
of the public good.

1025
01:00:05,898 --> 01:00:08,025
[Lively Irish music plays]

1026
01:00:08,150 --> 01:00:09,443
We all go someday.

1027
01:00:09,568 --> 01:00:10,444
Chin up.

1028
01:00:10,569 --> 01:00:11,820
Handsome bunch
of gallows fruit.

1029
01:00:11,945 --> 01:00:13,655
There's my old friend.
How are you feeling, Arthur?

1030
01:00:13,780 --> 01:00:15,199
I'm okay, I'm okay,
you know?

1031
01:00:15,324 --> 01:00:16,491
Oh, say hello to Amsterdam.

1032
01:00:16,617 --> 01:00:18,535
Nearly fishhooked McGloin
the other day.

1033
01:00:18,619 --> 01:00:19,912
- Nearly.
- How do you do?

1034
01:00:19,995 --> 01:00:21,914
I see you dressed
for the occasion, Arthur.

1035
01:00:21,997 --> 01:00:24,291
You know me, Bill...
always like to look me best.

1036
01:00:24,374 --> 01:00:25,501
That's the spirit.

1037
01:00:27,503 --> 01:00:29,630
That's a nice locket.
I'll give you a dollar for it.

1038
01:00:29,755 --> 01:00:31,465
It's me mother's.

1039
01:00:31,590 --> 01:00:33,967
Dollar and a half?

1040
01:00:34,092 --> 01:00:36,220
Done.

1041
01:00:36,303 --> 01:00:38,180
[Clasp opens]

1042
01:00:38,305 --> 01:00:40,015
[Jingling]

1043
01:00:40,140 --> 01:00:41,308
We'll miss you, Arthur.

1044
01:00:41,475 --> 01:00:42,935
See you in the hot country,
Seamus.

1045
01:00:43,060 --> 01:00:45,270
VENDOR: Hot corn!
Ears of early white corn!

1046
01:00:45,395 --> 01:00:46,939
Hot corn! Hot corn!

1047
01:00:47,064 --> 01:00:48,482
[Music continues]

1048
01:00:51,068 --> 01:00:53,111
Is my son present here?

1049
01:00:53,237 --> 01:00:54,446
[Music stops]

1050
01:00:54,530 --> 01:00:56,490
Where's my little fella?

1051
01:00:58,659 --> 01:01:00,827
Look at your da.

1052
01:01:00,953 --> 01:01:02,663
[Voice breaking]
Farewell, dear boy.

1053
01:01:03,956 --> 01:01:08,877
I never struck a foul blow,
nor turned a card!

1054
01:01:10,170 --> 01:01:13,924
May God greet me as a friend!

1055
01:01:14,049 --> 01:01:16,009
[Cheering]

1056
01:01:27,354 --> 01:01:30,566
[Irish music resumes,
crowd cheering]

1057
01:01:35,404 --> 01:01:37,322
<i>#...heart to fear #</i>

1058
01:01:37,739 --> 01:01:41,577
<i># And grace my fears relieved #</i>

1059
01:01:41,660 --> 01:01:45,497
<i># How precious</i>
<i>did that grace appear #</i>

1060
01:01:45,581 --> 01:01:48,709
AMSTERDAM: That night,
the reformers held a dance.

1061
01:01:48,876 --> 01:01:51,336
That was the Five Points,
all right...

1062
01:01:51,461 --> 01:01:54,381
hangings of a morning,
dancings of an evening.

1063
01:01:54,464 --> 01:01:55,465
Ow!

1064
01:01:55,591 --> 01:01:57,718
...sure meself, but it's not
a matter of words.

1065
01:01:57,843 --> 01:01:59,678
I can tell by the way
she smiles at me.

1066
01:01:59,761 --> 01:02:01,555
Well, she smiles
at a lot of people, Johnny.

1067
01:02:01,638 --> 01:02:03,515
- Sir...
- You don't know her.

1068
01:02:03,599 --> 01:02:06,727
A penny of gratitude for
a fighting Irishman, young sir.

1069
01:02:06,852 --> 01:02:09,730
[Choir singing continues
in distance]

1070
01:02:09,855 --> 01:02:11,231
You're from Kerry?

1071
01:02:11,315 --> 01:02:13,233
I am, sir. I am.

1072
01:02:14,443 --> 01:02:15,485
Look, it ain't much.

1073
01:02:15,569 --> 01:02:17,070
Thank you, sir.
Thank you.

1074
01:02:17,154 --> 01:02:18,697
REV. RALEIGH:
Ladies and gentlemen,

1075
01:02:18,822 --> 01:02:21,158
we are delighted to see
so many young faces

1076
01:02:21,283 --> 01:02:23,452
in our first annual
Mission dance.

1077
01:02:23,577 --> 01:02:25,746
This'll be
a real ballum rancum, eh?

1078
01:02:25,913 --> 01:02:28,582
The Mission welcomes Christians
of every stamp,

1079
01:02:28,707 --> 01:02:30,459
and we are
particularly happy

1080
01:02:30,584 --> 01:02:32,586
to greet
our Roman-Catholic friends

1081
01:02:32,711 --> 01:02:34,922
who join us here tonight.

1082
01:02:35,047 --> 01:02:37,424
Ladies, come with me.
Come with me.

1083
01:02:37,549 --> 01:02:39,218
Sit with us.
[Chuckles]

1084
01:02:39,301 --> 01:02:43,096
We're going to start
the dancing in just a moment.

1085
01:02:43,222 --> 01:02:45,224
Good evening, Reverend.

1086
01:02:45,349 --> 01:02:47,768
Good evening, Your Holiness.

1087
01:02:47,893 --> 01:02:49,394
[Women laughing]

1088
01:02:49,520 --> 01:02:51,021
Good evening, Reverend.

1089
01:02:51,104 --> 01:02:54,566
Looks as though
you should have shaved closer.

1090
01:02:56,652 --> 01:02:57,694
Oh.

1091
01:02:57,819 --> 01:02:59,446
Good evening, Reverend.

1092
01:02:59,613 --> 01:03:01,365
I do beg your pardon.

1093
01:03:05,619 --> 01:03:07,246
Miss..?

1094
01:03:09,081 --> 01:03:10,999
Uh...

1095
01:03:11,124 --> 01:03:12,459
Everdeane.

1096
01:03:12,584 --> 01:03:14,628
Miss Everdeane.

1097
01:03:18,715 --> 01:03:20,717
[Women giggle]

1098
01:03:26,306 --> 01:03:29,852
Now, gentlemen, over here,
if you don't mind.

1099
01:03:29,977 --> 01:03:30,978
Thank you.

1100
01:03:31,103 --> 01:03:32,646
Open it.

1101
01:03:32,813 --> 01:03:34,773
Hold it up.

1102
01:03:36,942 --> 01:03:38,986
Into the mirror.

1103
01:03:41,321 --> 01:03:42,823
[Chuckles softly]

1104
01:03:45,951 --> 01:03:47,494
Hmm...

1105
01:03:53,542 --> 01:03:55,627
[Inhales deeply]

1106
01:03:55,711 --> 01:03:57,337
Mmm...

1107
01:03:57,462 --> 01:03:59,339
[Chuckles]

1108
01:04:00,632 --> 01:04:04,136
[Music box playing]

1109
01:04:06,513 --> 01:04:08,640
[Chuckles softly]

1110
01:04:19,776 --> 01:04:21,320
All right.

1111
01:04:31,455 --> 01:04:33,081
That one.

1112
01:04:35,250 --> 01:04:37,169
Our queen has chosen.

1113
01:04:37,252 --> 01:04:41,381
[Mid-tempo music plays]

1114
01:04:56,355 --> 01:04:57,731
Sir...

1115
01:04:57,814 --> 01:04:58,857
your lady.

1116
01:04:58,982 --> 01:05:00,317
Right.

1117
01:05:00,400 --> 01:05:03,862
Regular services are held
at the church at 6:00 and 8:00.

1118
01:05:03,987 --> 01:05:05,113
Go to hell.

1119
01:05:13,914 --> 01:05:15,666
What do you think
you're doing?

1120
01:05:15,749 --> 01:05:16,708
I'm dancing.

1121
01:05:16,834 --> 01:05:18,293
I said why'd you pick me?

1122
01:05:18,418 --> 01:05:20,003
That's none of your business.

1123
01:05:20,087 --> 01:05:21,338
Would you mind telling me?

1124
01:05:21,421 --> 01:05:22,339
Ohh!

1125
01:05:22,422 --> 01:05:23,757
AMSTERDAM: I'm sorry.

1126
01:05:23,882 --> 01:05:25,050
[Jenny gasps]

1127
01:05:25,133 --> 01:05:26,343
God damn it.

1128
01:05:26,426 --> 01:05:27,427
[Gasps]

1129
01:05:27,553 --> 01:05:28,595
- Ow!
- Sorry.

1130
01:05:28,720 --> 01:05:29,930
[Clears throat]

1131
01:05:30,055 --> 01:05:31,557
I'm not much of a dancer.

1132
01:05:31,640 --> 01:05:33,725
Just try to keep calm.

1133
01:05:33,851 --> 01:05:35,811
I've never been
to a stepping-ken before.

1134
01:05:35,936 --> 01:05:37,938
It's best not to look down.

1135
01:05:39,982 --> 01:05:42,442
You can hold me tighter
if you like.

1136
01:05:49,908 --> 01:05:50,826
All right.

1137
01:05:50,951 --> 01:05:52,286
All right.

1138
01:05:54,079 --> 01:05:56,373
So, why didn't you dance
with Johnny?

1139
01:05:58,250 --> 01:06:00,085
Because...

1140
01:06:02,296 --> 01:06:04,339
...I didn't want him.

1141
01:07:01,939 --> 01:07:03,941
[Gasps]
I'm not wanting this.

1142
01:07:04,024 --> 01:07:05,108
[Sighs]

1143
01:07:05,192 --> 01:07:06,693
Mmm...

1144
01:07:06,777 --> 01:07:08,362
[Sighs]

1145
01:07:12,074 --> 01:07:12,991
Wait.

1146
01:07:13,075 --> 01:07:13,992
What?

1147
01:07:14,076 --> 01:07:15,244
Wait.

1148
01:07:15,369 --> 01:07:16,703
How does this open?

1149
01:07:16,828 --> 01:07:18,497
It takes too long
to lace back up.

1150
01:07:18,580 --> 01:07:20,791
We'll be here all night.

1151
01:07:20,916 --> 01:07:22,376
[Exhales deeply]

1152
01:07:32,719 --> 01:07:35,264
Sure, all right.
I'll take it off.

1153
01:07:44,189 --> 01:07:46,275
[Panting]

1154
01:07:56,952 --> 01:07:59,872
There was a baby.
They cut it out.

1155
01:08:04,168 --> 01:08:05,878
I'm sorry.

1156
01:08:07,254 --> 01:08:09,339
No, it's fine.

1157
01:08:12,926 --> 01:08:15,387
Have you got any scars?

1158
01:08:17,055 --> 01:08:19,016
One or two.

1159
01:08:19,099 --> 01:08:22,436
[Guitar music playing,
singing in distance]

1160
01:09:16,740 --> 01:09:18,283
What's that, then?

1161
01:09:18,408 --> 01:09:23,497
That... is a gift
from Mr. Cutting.

1162
01:09:27,251 --> 01:09:28,502
A gift?

1163
01:09:30,003 --> 01:09:31,213
A gift.

1164
01:09:33,173 --> 01:09:34,800
Was it your birthday?

1165
01:09:34,925 --> 01:09:36,134
[Laughs]

1166
01:09:36,260 --> 01:09:37,803
No.

1167
01:09:41,598 --> 01:09:43,725
What'd you give <i>him,</i> then?

1168
01:09:46,061 --> 01:09:49,273
The answer to that
has nothing to do with you.

1169
01:09:55,362 --> 01:09:57,573
Don't tell me
you're angry with me.

1170
01:09:57,698 --> 01:09:58,574
No.

1171
01:09:58,699 --> 01:10:00,367
I'm through with you.

1172
01:10:02,536 --> 01:10:04,204
[Gasps]

1173
01:10:04,329 --> 01:10:07,833
Well... you're quicker
than most fellows.

1174
01:10:07,958 --> 01:10:10,085
Generally,
they wait till afterwards.

1175
01:10:10,210 --> 01:10:12,588
Well, I ain't interested
in the Butcher's leavings.

1176
01:10:12,713 --> 01:10:15,716
[Drumbeats, chanting
in distance]

1177
01:10:23,265 --> 01:10:25,767
[Drumbeats, chanting continue]

1178
01:10:28,395 --> 01:10:30,480
[Indistinct shouting]

1179
01:10:32,566 --> 01:10:35,903
Hey! Bill says
keep clear of the pikers.

1180
01:10:36,028 --> 01:10:38,238
15 to 1, Bug-Eye Moran.

1181
01:10:38,363 --> 01:10:39,740
Amsterdam!

1182
01:10:39,865 --> 01:10:42,201
AMSTERDAM: Everyone was
working for the Butcher.

1183
01:10:42,326 --> 01:10:44,203
We ran his errands,
made his money,

1184
01:10:44,286 --> 01:10:46,371
took a piece
and said, "Thank you, sir."

1185
01:10:46,496 --> 01:10:47,414
TWEED:
Gentlemen, it's a raid.

1186
01:10:47,497 --> 01:10:49,041
AMSTERDAM: Even Tweed.

1187
01:10:49,166 --> 01:10:50,375
The fight's over!

1188
01:10:50,501 --> 01:10:51,543
AMSTERDAM: Even me...

1189
01:10:51,668 --> 01:10:53,128
[Indistinct shouting]

1190
01:10:53,253 --> 01:10:54,630
...my father's son.

1191
01:10:54,755 --> 01:10:57,216
- What the hell is this?
- Sorry, Bill.

1192
01:10:57,299 --> 01:11:00,302
The city ordinance against
boxiana's a blight, I grant...

1193
01:11:00,427 --> 01:11:02,429
I'm losing revenue
while you speechify.

1194
01:11:02,554 --> 01:11:04,306
Get out there
and collect those bets!

1195
01:11:04,431 --> 01:11:06,266
Sir, how do I collect
if no one won the fight?

1196
01:11:06,391 --> 01:11:08,894
This counts as a no-decision.
You got that covered, right?

1197
01:11:09,019 --> 01:11:11,605
Didn't anybody pay off
the goddamn police?

1198
01:11:11,730 --> 01:11:14,441
We paid the Municipal Police.
This is the Metropolitan Police.

1199
01:11:14,566 --> 01:11:15,901
You are gonna repay me
every cent.

1200
01:11:16,026 --> 01:11:17,611
- Mister Tweed...
- Who asked for your opinion?!

1201
01:11:17,778 --> 01:11:20,572
Let him speak!
He don't answer to you!

1202
01:11:20,656 --> 01:11:23,116
The law says that there's
no boxing in the city.

1203
01:11:23,242 --> 01:11:24,993
That's right...
in the city.

1204
01:11:25,118 --> 01:11:26,870
Well, where's the city end?

1205
01:11:29,831 --> 01:11:32,376
[Grunts]

1206
01:11:32,459 --> 01:11:33,877
[Crowd cheering]

1207
01:11:33,961 --> 01:11:37,965
REFEREE: The winner
in the 75th round...

1208
01:11:38,090 --> 01:11:40,384
BARNUM: Allow me
to acknowledge the man

1209
01:11:40,467 --> 01:11:42,886
whose vision and enterprise
made possible

1210
01:11:42,970 --> 01:11:46,181
the staging
of this noble combat

1211
01:11:46,306 --> 01:11:50,102
in these awe-inspiring and
entirely legal surroundings,

1212
01:11:50,227 --> 01:11:52,145
Mr. William Cutting!

1213
01:11:52,271 --> 01:11:53,730
[Crowd cheering]

1214
01:11:53,856 --> 01:11:55,858
[Indistinct shouting]

1215
01:11:55,983 --> 01:11:57,401
And...

1216
01:11:57,484 --> 01:11:59,778
and his young associate!

1217
01:11:59,862 --> 01:12:01,864
[Crowd cheering]

1218
01:12:08,120 --> 01:12:10,539
Good.
You done very good.

1219
01:12:10,664 --> 01:12:13,500
Well, we done good.
We done all right.

1220
01:12:13,625 --> 01:12:15,335
BARNUM: And while I have
your kind attention...

1221
01:12:15,460 --> 01:12:16,670
It was a good show.

1222
01:12:16,795 --> 01:12:18,672
...may I remind you
of the further wonders

1223
01:12:18,797 --> 01:12:23,385
that await you at my museum,
located on Broadway...

1224
01:12:23,510 --> 01:12:26,930
P.T. Barnum's
Gallery of Wonders!

1225
01:12:27,055 --> 01:12:29,474
- Watch who you're shoving!
- Keep your hands to yourself!

1226
01:12:29,558 --> 01:12:30,642
That's my money!

1227
01:12:30,767 --> 01:12:32,978
Get your hands
out of me pocket!

1228
01:12:33,061 --> 01:12:34,897
Stop it! Stop it!

1229
01:12:35,022 --> 01:12:36,899
AMSTERDAM:
It's a funny feeling

1230
01:12:37,024 --> 01:12:40,194
being took under the wing
of a dragon.

1231
01:12:40,277 --> 01:12:42,821
It's warmer than you think.

1232
01:12:42,946 --> 01:12:44,990
TWEED: That's the building
of our country

1233
01:12:45,115 --> 01:12:48,577
right there, Mr. Cutting...
Americans aborning.

1234
01:12:48,702 --> 01:12:50,370
I don't see no Americans.

1235
01:12:50,495 --> 01:12:53,540
I see trespassers...
Irish harps.

1236
01:12:53,665 --> 01:12:56,168
Do a job for a nickel
what a nigger does for a dime

1237
01:12:56,335 --> 01:12:58,462
and a white man
used to get a quarter for.

1238
01:12:58,587 --> 01:13:00,881
What have they done? Name
one thing they've contributed.

1239
01:13:01,006 --> 01:13:02,007
Votes.

1240
01:13:02,174 --> 01:13:03,175
Votes, you say?

1241
01:13:03,342 --> 01:13:05,093
They vote how the archbishop
tells them,

1242
01:13:05,219 --> 01:13:06,553
and who tells the archbishop?

1243
01:13:06,678 --> 01:13:10,057
Their king in the pointy hat
what sits on his throne in Rome.

1244
01:13:11,183 --> 01:13:14,436
Bill's got mixed feelings
as regards the Irish.

1245
01:13:14,561 --> 01:13:17,064
Bill... deliver
these good and fervent folk

1246
01:13:17,189 --> 01:13:19,191
to the polls
on a regular basis,

1247
01:13:19,316 --> 01:13:20,859
and there'll be
a handsome price

1248
01:13:20,943 --> 01:13:22,819
for each vote
that goes Tammany's way.

1249
01:13:24,238 --> 01:13:26,406
[Spits]

1250
01:13:26,532 --> 01:13:28,408
My father gave his life

1251
01:13:28,575 --> 01:13:30,577
making this country
what it is...

1252
01:13:30,744 --> 01:13:32,704
murdered by the British
with all of his men

1253
01:13:32,829 --> 01:13:36,124
on the 25th of July,
<i>anno Domini</i> 1814.

1254
01:13:36,250 --> 01:13:38,877
You think I'm gonna help you
befoul his legacy

1255
01:13:38,961 --> 01:13:40,879
by giving this country
over to them

1256
01:13:40,963 --> 01:13:42,965
what's had no hand
in the fighting for it?

1257
01:13:43,090 --> 01:13:44,550
Why? Because they come off
a boat,

1258
01:13:44,633 --> 01:13:46,426
crawling with lice
and begging you for soup?

1259
01:13:46,552 --> 01:13:47,928
Tsk, tsk.

1260
01:13:48,053 --> 01:13:50,722
You're a great one for
the fighting, Bill, I know.

1261
01:13:50,806 --> 01:13:52,099
But you can't fight forever.

1262
01:13:52,224 --> 01:13:54,142
- I can go down doing it.
- And you will.

1263
01:13:58,772 --> 01:14:00,065
What did you say?

1264
01:14:00,148 --> 01:14:04,236
I said you're turning
your back on the future.

1265
01:14:06,405 --> 01:14:08,782
Not <i>our</i> future.

1266
01:14:13,704 --> 01:14:15,455
That document makes you
a citizen.

1267
01:14:15,581 --> 01:14:17,875
This one makes you a private
in the Union Army.

1268
01:14:17,958 --> 01:14:19,835
Now go fight for your country.

1269
01:14:19,960 --> 01:14:20,919
Next!

1270
01:14:21,003 --> 01:14:22,379
<i># Well, meself</i>
<i>And a hundred more #</i>

1271
01:14:22,421 --> 01:14:24,131
Sign here, son.
Or make your mark.

1272
01:14:24,256 --> 01:14:26,633
<i># To America sailed o'er #</i>

1273
01:14:26,758 --> 01:14:32,389
<i># Our fortunes to be made,</i>
<i>We were thinkin' #</i>

1274
01:14:32,514 --> 01:14:35,517
<i># When we got to Yankee land #</i>

1275
